their own economic security. The Burdens of Aspiration explores the imprint of the region’s success-driven public culture, the realities of increasing social and economic insecurity, and models of success emphasized in contemporary public schools for the region’s working and middle class youth. Focused on two disparate groups of students-low-income, “at-risk” Latino youth attending a specialized program exposing youth to high tech industry within an “under-performing” public high school, and middle-income white and Asian students attending a “high-performing” public school with informal connections to the tech elite-Elsa Davidson offers an in-depth look at the process of forming aspirations across lines of race and class. By analyzing the successes and sometimes unanticipated effects of the schools' attempts to shape the aspirations and values of their students, she provides keen insights into the role schooling plays in social reproduction, and how dynamics of race and class inform ideas about responsible citizenship that are instilled in America's youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEducationxSocial aspectsxCaliforniaxSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aEducationxSocial aspectszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aEducational equalizationxCaliforniaxSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aEducational equalizationzCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aPolarization (Social sciences)xCaliforniaxSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County)xCaliforniaxSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aPolarization (Social sciences)zCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aStudent aspirationsxCaliforniaxSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aStudent aspirationszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County). 0aYouthxSocial conditions